display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> be a set, and let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathtt {P}{\mathopen {}\left (\mathtt {x},\mathtt {y}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> be a formula in the language of set theory such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  i\in  I\mathpunct {.} \exists ! S\mathpunct {.} \mathtt {P}{\mathopen {}\left (i,S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> holds. Then the collection of sets <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathtt {P}{\mathopen {}\left (i,S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> holds for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in  I]]></fr:tex> holds forms a set.</fr:p><fr:p>This is <fr:em>almost</fr:em> saying that the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00N6.xml"
addr="jms-00N6"
title="Direct image">direct image</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> under <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathtt {P}]]></fr:tex> is a set, but this doesn’t actually make sense because we do not have a way to speak about a “relation” between a set and the class of all sets. This strange situation is clarified by other foundational system that go beyond the limitations of the Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory that we have studied in this course.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
